# To [[connect]] or [[assemble]] pieces using a bolt.
#: '''''Bolt''' the vice to the bench.''
# To [[secure]] a [[door]] by locking or barring it.
#: '' '''Bolt''' the door.''
#* '''1851''', [[w:Herman Melville|Herman Melville]], ''[[w:Moby Dick|Moby Dick]]'', [[s:Moby-Dick/Chapter 24|chapter 24]]
#*: If that double-'''bolted''' land, Japan, is ever to become hospitable, it is the whale-ship alone to whom the credit will be due; for already she is on the threshold.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To flee, to depart, to [[accelerate]] suddenly.
#: ''Seeing the snake, the horse '''bolted'''.''
#: ''The actor forgot his line and '''bolted''' from the stage.''
#* Drayton
#*: This Puck seems but a dreaming dolt, {{...}} / And oft out of a bush doth '''bolt'''.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To cause to start or spring forth; to dislodge (an animal being hunted).
#: ''to '''bolt''' a rabbit''
# To strike or fall suddenly like a bolt.
#* Milton
#*: His cloudless thunder '''bolted''' on their heads.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To [[escape]].
# {{context|intransitive|botany|lang=en}} Of a plant, to [[grow]] quickly; to go to [[seed]].
#: ''Lettuce and spinach will '''bolt''' as the weather warms up.''
# To swallow food without chewing it.
#* '''1859''' Darwin, Charles, ''On the Origin of Species'', ch 11, p 362:
#*: ''Some hawks and owls '''bolt''' their prey whole, and after an interval of from twelve to twenty hours disgorge pellets.''
# To drink one's drink very quickly; to [[down]] a drink.
#: ''Come on, everyone, '''bolt''' your drinks; I want to go to the next pub!''
# {{context|US|politics|lang=en}} To refuse to support a [[nomination]] made by a [[party]] or [[caucus]] with which one has been connected; to break away from a party.
# To utter [[precipitately]]; to blurt or throw out.
#* Milton
#*: I hate when Vice can '''bolt''' her arguments.

